<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,942,1617]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1158,1184]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Morphology</emphasis>
. Small-sized snail (conical shell up to 
<quantity box="[770,833,1158,1185]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
long/high). Shell is striated, with 5–6 step-like whorls. Aperture is oval, umbilicus is open and deep. For more details see 
<bibRefCitation author="Welter-Schultes, F. W." box="[904,1201,1194,1220]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refId="ref60074" refString="Welter-Schultes, F. W. (2012) European non-marine molluscs, a guide for species identification, planet poster editions. Planet Poster Editions, Gottingen, 674 pp. [in German]" type="book" year="2012">Welter-Schultes (2012: 49</bibRefCitation>
, figure at the bottom of the page).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,942,1617]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,496,1266,1292]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Distribution and ecology</emphasis>
. Holarctic species. Amphibious semi-terrestrial snail preferring small water bodies (meadows, ponds, marshes, brooks) and temporal habitats (
<bibRefCitation author="Trouve, S. &amp; Degen, L. &amp; Goudet, J." box="[809,1010,1302,1329]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="358 - 370" refId="ref58266" refString="Trouve, S., Degen, L. &amp; Goudet, J. (2005) Ecological components and evolution of selfing in the freshwater snail Galba truncatula. Journal of Evolutionary Biology, 18 (2), 358 - 370. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1420 - 9101.2004.00831. x" type="journal article" year="2005">
Trouve 
<emphasis box="[897,945,1302,1328]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
2005
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Welter-Schultes, F. W." box="[1020,1264,1302,1328]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refId="ref60074" refString="Welter-Schultes, F. W. (2012) European non-marine molluscs, a guide for species identification, planet poster editions. Planet Poster Editions, Gottingen, 674 pp. [in German]" type="book" year="2012">Welter-Schultes 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dreyfuss, G. &amp; Vignoles, P. &amp; Rondelaud, D. &amp; Cabaret, J." pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refId="ref45367" refString="Dreyfuss, G., Vignoles, P., Rondelaud, D. &amp; Cabaret, J. (2015) The mud snail (Galba truncatula) Ecology, parasitism and control. Lap Lambert Academic Publishing, Chisinau, 243 pp." type="book" year="2015">
Dreyfuss 
<emphasis box="[1381,1429,1302,1328]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
. 2015
</bibRefCitation>
). Fairly scarce findings in 
<collectingCountry box="[507,579,1338,1364]" name="Serbia" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Serbia</collectingCountry>
include the Danube River, and few smaller watercourses (Vlasina, Moravica and Veternica Rivers, Kudoški canal) and Obedska bara Wetland.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,942,1617]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,378,1410,1436]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Other remarks</emphasis>
. Shell morphology can be very variable, particularly in regard to spire height. It could be misidentified as degenerated forms of 
<taxonomicName authority="(O. F. Muller, 1774) (Gloer 2019)" authorityName="Gloer" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="O. F. Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1774" box="[545,1164,1446,1472]" class="Gastropoda" family="Lymnaeidae" genus="Stagnicola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hygrophila" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="palustris">
<emphasis box="[545,772,1446,1472]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Stagnicola palustris</emphasis>
(O.F. Müller, 1774) (
<bibRefCitation author="Gloer, P." box="[1021,1157,1446,1472]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refId="ref47000" refString="Gloer, P. (2019) The freshwater gastropods of the West-Palaearctis. Biodiversity Research Laboratory, Hetlingen, 399 pp." type="book" year="2019">Glöer 2019</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. In Europe, it is known as an intermediate host for trematodes (
<emphasis box="[601,816,1482,1508]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fascicola hepatica</emphasis>
and others) thus serving as a disease vector (details in 
<bibRefCitation author="Dreyfuss, G. &amp; Vignoles, P. &amp; Rondelaud, D. &amp; Cabaret, J." box="[151,382,1518,1545]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refId="ref45367" refString="Dreyfuss, G., Vignoles, P., Rondelaud, D. &amp; Cabaret, J. (2015) The mud snail (Galba truncatula) Ecology, parasitism and control. Lap Lambert Academic Publishing, Chisinau, 243 pp." type="book" year="2015">
Dreyfuss 
<emphasis box="[261,312,1518,1544]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). In some habitats with low population densities, or even individual presence of snails, selffertilization is common (
<bibRefCitation author="Trouve, S. &amp; Degen, L. &amp; Goudet, J." box="[433,651,1554,1581]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="358 - 370" refId="ref58266" refString="Trouve, S., Degen, L. &amp; Goudet, J. (2005) Ecological components and evolution of selfing in the freshwater snail Galba truncatula. Journal of Evolutionary Biology, 18 (2), 358 - 370. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1420 - 9101.2004.00831. x" type="journal article" year="2005">
Trouve 
<emphasis box="[523,575,1554,1580]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
. 2005
</bibRefCitation>
). On the IUCN Red List it has been assessed as LC (
<bibRefCitation author="Van Damme, D. &amp; Kebapcy, U." pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="4833123" refId="ref58825" refString="Van Damme, D. &amp; Kebapcy, U. (2011 a) Galba truncatula. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, 2011, e. T 155730 A 4833123. [downloaded 3 May 2021]" type="journal article" year="2011">
<collectingRegion box="[1262,1308,1554,1580]" country="Turkey" name="Van" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Van</collectingRegion>
Damme &amp; Kebapçý 2011 
<emphasis box="[313,327,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">a</emphasis>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
